4.7. A one dimensional damped wave equation

4.7.1. Linear damping.In this section, we discuss an example due to Webb [1979b]. Although more general results will be given in the next section, it is instructive to do the one dimensional case first because all Sobolev estimates are very simple.

Let $L^{2}=L^{2}(0, \pi , R), H^{k}=H^{k}([0, \pi ], R),\, H_{0}^{k}=H_{0}^{k}([0, \pi ], R)$. For a given $\alpha >0$ consider the equation for a function $u(x, t)$:

7.1 $$\begin{equation} u_{tt}+2\alpha u_{t}-u_{xx}=f(u)-g \cssId{texmlid273}{\tag{7.1}} \end{equation}$$

with the boundary conditions

7.2 $$\begin{equation} u(0, t)=u(\pi , t)=0 \cssId{texmlid110}{\tag{7.2}} \end{equation}$$

or, equivalently, the system

7.3 $$\begin{equation} u_{t}=v,\qquad \upsilon _{t}=u_{xx}-2\alpha v +f(u) \cssId{texmlid112}{\tag{7.3}} \end{equation}$$

with the boundary conditions (7.2). We take the initial data $(\phi , \psi )$ for $u, v$ at $t=0$ to be in $H_{0}^{1} \times L^{2}$. Observe that we can take $|\phi |_{H_{0}^{1}}^{2}=|\phi ^{\prime }|_{L^{2}}$.

The function $f$ will be required to satisfy

7.4 $$\begin{equation} f\in C^{2}(R, R),\qquad \varlimsup _{|u|\rightarrow \infty }f(u)/u\leq 0,\qquad f(0)=0, \cssId{texmlid111}{\tag{7.4}} \end{equation}$$

and $g$ is assumed to be in $L^{2}(0, \pi )$.

The main result of this section is

4.7.2. A bifurcation problem.In this section, we consider the equation

7.15 $$\begin{equation} \begin{split} u_{tt}+2\alpha &u_{t}-u_{xx}=\lambda f(u),\qquad 0<x<\pi ,\ t\geq 0,\\ &u=0\quad {\text{ at }} x=0,\ x=\pi \end{split} \cssId{texmlid118}{\tag{7.15}} \end{equation}$$

where $\alpha >0,\ \lambda >0$ is a parameter, $f\in C^{2}(R)$, and

7.16 $$\begin{align} \left\{\begin{array}{l} f(0)=0,\qquad f^{\prime }(0)=1,\\\varlimsup _{|x|\rightarrow \infty }f(x)/x\leq 0,\\\mathrm{sgn}\, f^{\prime \prime }(x)= -\mathrm{sgn}\, x\, \quad \mathrm{for}\ x\in R. \end{array}\right. \cssId{texmlid119}{\tag{7.16}} \end{align}$$

The set $E$ of equilibrium points of (7.15) is bounded under condition (7.16). If we treat $\lambda$ as a bifurcation parameter, then the bifurcation diagram is essentially the same as the one in 4.3.3 for $f(u)=u-u^{3}$ (see Figure 3.5). For $\lambda \in (n^{2},\, (n+1)^{2})$, there are exactly $2n+1$ equilibrium points $\phi _{0}=0,\, \phi _{j}^{+},\, \phi _{j}^{-},\, j=1,2,\ldots , n,\, \phi _{j}^{+}{}^{\prime }(0)>0,\, \phi _{j}^{-}{}^{\prime }(0)<0$, and $\phi _{j}^{\pm }$ have exactly $(j-1)$ zeros in $(0, \pi )$ and sign $f(\phi _{j}^{\pm }(x))=$ sgn $\phi _{j}^{+}(x)$ for $x\in (0, \pi )$.

For the parabolic equation in $\S$4.3.3, we observed that, if $\lambda \in (0,1),$ then $\phi _{0}$ is asymptotically stable and, if $\lambda \in (n^{2},\, (n+1)^{2}),\, n\geq 1$, then $\phi _{1}^{+},\, \phi _{1}^{-}$ are asymptotically stable, $\dim W^{u}(\phi _{0})=n$, and $\dim W^{u}(\phi _{j}^{\pm })=j$. It is interesting that the same results are valid for the hyperbolic equation as was observed by Webb [1973b]. Using Theorem4.7.1, we can say more.

4.7.3. Nonlinear damping.Suppose $f$ satisfies (7.4), $g \in L^{2}(\Omega )$,

7.17 $$\begin{equation} h\in C^{1}(R, R),\quad h(0)=0,\quad \quad 0<\alpha \leq h^{\prime }(u)\leq \beta \quad \mathrm{for}\, u\in R, \cssId{texmlid121}{\tag{7.17}} \end{equation}$$

where $\alpha , \beta$ are positive constants and consider the nonlinearly damped wave equation

7.18 $$\begin{equation} u_{t}=v,\quad \quad v_{t}=u_{xx}+f(u)-g-h(v) \cssId{texmlid120}{\tag{7.18}} \end{equation}$$

with the Dirichlet conditions (7.2). The main result of this section is based on Lopes and Ceron [1984] and is the extension of Theorem4.7.1 to equation (7.18), namely,

$$\begin{equation*} A_{f,h}=\bigcup _{(\phi ,0)\in E} W^{u}(\phi , 0). \end{equation*}$$

Much of the same proof as used for the proof of Theorem 4.7.1 can be used here. In fact, using the same arguments as before, one obtains that $T(t)(\phi , \psi )$ is defined for $t\geq 0$, orbits of bounded sets are bounded, and $E$ is bounded. When $h(v)=2\alpha v$, we employed the variation of constants formula to show that $T(t)$ was an $\alpha$-contraction. Another idea is needed when $h$ is nonlinear. We show that the conditions of Theorem 2.3.6 are satisfied for the map $T(t_{1})$ for some $t_{1}>0$. The appropriate estimates are obtained by using a Lyapunov function different from the one in (7.9).

Let $(\,{,}\,)$ be the $L^{2}$ inner product and define

7.19 $$\begin{equation} E(\phi , \psi )=\frac{1}{2}|\psi |_{L^{2}}^{2}+2b(\phi , \psi )+\frac{1}{2}|\phi _{x}|_{L^{2}}^{2}, \cssId{texmlid128}{\tag{7.19}} \end{equation}$$

where $b>0$ is a constant such that

7.20 $$\begin{equation} b<\min \left(\frac{1}{4}, \frac{2\alpha }{4+\beta ^{2}}\right). \cssId{texmlid123}{\tag{7.20}} \end{equation}$$

Then there are positive constants $k_{1}, k_{2}$ such that

7.21 $$\begin{equation} k_{1}(|\psi |_{L^{2}}^{2}+|\phi _{x}|_{L^{2}}^{2})\leq E(\phi , \psi )\leq k_{2}(|\psi |_{L^{2}}^{2}+|\phi _{x}|_{L^{2}}^{2}). \cssId{texmlid124}{\tag{7.21}} \end{equation}$$

Let $(u_{1}, v_{1}), (u_{2}, v_{2})$ be two solutions of (7.2), (7.18). We know that $|u_{j}(t)|_{H_{0}^{1}}, |v_{j}(t)|_{L^{2}}$ are bounded by some constant $R_{1}$ for $t\geq 0$. If $\zeta (t)=u_{1}(t)-u_{2}(t), \eta (t)=v_{1}(t)-v_{2}(t)$, and $|\cdot |$ denotes $|\cdot |_{L^{2}}$, then

$$\begin{align*} \frac{d}{dt}E(\zeta (t), \eta (t))&=-(\eta , h(v_{1})-h(v_{2}))+2b|\eta |^{2}-2b(\zeta , h(v_{1})-h(v_{2}))\\ &\quad -2b|\zeta _{x}|^{2}+2b(\zeta , f(u_{1})-f(u_{2}))+(\eta , f(u_{1})-f(u_{2}))\\ &\leq -(\alpha -2b)|\eta |^{2}+2b\beta |\zeta |\cdot |\eta |-2b|\zeta _{x}|^{2}\\ &\quad +2b(\zeta , f(u_{1})-f(u_{2}))+(\eta , f(u_{1})-f(u_{2}))\\ &\leq -(\alpha -2b)|\eta |^{2}+2b\beta |_{\zeta _{x}}|\cdot |\eta |-2b|\zeta _{x}|^{2}\\ &\quad +(2b|\zeta |+|\eta |)|f(u_{1})-f(u_{2})|\\ &\leq -\theta (|\eta |^{2}+|\zeta _{x}|^{2})+K|f(u_{1})-f(u_{2})|\\ &\leq -\frac{\theta }{k_{1}}E(\zeta (t), \eta (t))+K|f(u_{1}(t))-f(u_{2}(t))| \end{align*}$$

for some constant $\theta >0$ since $b$ satisfies (7.20), relation (7.21) is satisfied, and $|u_{j}(t)|_{H_{0}^{1}}, |v_{j}(t)|_{L^{2}}$ are bounded for $t\geq 0$. This last inequality implies that there is a constant $K_{1}$ such that, for all $t\geq 0$,

7.22 $$\begin{equation} E(\zeta (t), \eta (t))\leq e^{-\theta t/k_{1}}E(\zeta (0), \eta (0))+K_{1}\sup _{0\leq s\leq t}|f(u_{1}(s))-f(u_{2}(s))|_{L^{2}}. \cssId{texmlid132}{\tag{7.22}} \end{equation}$$

From (7.21), this implies that there are constants $K_{2}, K_{3}$ such that

7.23 $$\begin{equation} \begin{split} |(\zeta (t), \eta (t))|_{H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}}&\leq K_{2}e^{-\theta t/k_{1}}|(\zeta (0), \eta (0))|_{H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}}\\ &\quad +K_{3}\sup _{0\leq s\leq t}|f(u_{1}(s))-f(u_{2}(s))|_{L^{2}}. \end{split} \cssId{texmlid125}{\tag{7.23}} \end{equation}$$

Since $u_{j}(t)$ is bounded in $H_{0}^{1}$, we have $|u_{j}(t, x)|\leq \sqrt {\pi }|u_{j}(t)|_{H_{0}^{1}}$ and there is a constant $K_{4}$ such that

7.24 $$\begin{equation} |f(u_{1}(s))-f(u_{2}(s))|_{L^{2}}=\left|\int _{u_{1}(s,\cdot )}^{u_{2}(s,\cdot )}f^{\prime }(\tau )d\tau \right|_{L^{2}}\leq K_{4}|u_{1}(s)-u_{2}(s)|_{L^{2}}. \cssId{texmlid126}{\tag{7.24}} \end{equation}$$

Choose $t_{1}>0$ so that the constant $q=\exp (-\theta t/k_{1})<1$. Let $w_{1}^{0}= (u_{1}(0), v_{1}(0)), w_{2}^{0}=(u_{2}(0), v_{2}(0))$. Then (7.23), (7.24) imply that

7.25 $$\begin{equation} |T(t_{1})w_{1}^{0}-T(t_{1})w_{2}^{0}|_{H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}}\leq q|w_{1}^{0}-w_{2}^{0}|_{H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}}+\rho (w_{1}^{0}, w_{2}^{0}), \cssId{texmlid278}{\tag{7.25}} \end{equation}$$

where

$$\begin{equation*} \rho (w_{1}^{0}, w_{2}^{0})=K_{3}K_{4}\sup _{0\leq s\leq t_{1}}|u_{1}(s)-u_{2}(s)|_{L^{2}}. \end{equation*}$$

The function $\rho (w_{1}^{0}, w_{2}^{0})$ is a pseudometric on $H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}$. To show that $\rho$ is precompact, suppose $w_{n}^{0}$ is a bounded sequence in $H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}$ and let $(u_{n}(t), v_{n}(t))$ be the solution through $w_{n}^{0}$ at $t=0$. Since orbits of bounded sets are bounded, the sequence $(u_{n}(t), v_{n}(t))$ is bounded in $H_{0}^{1}\times L^{2}$ uniformly for $t\geq 0$. Therefore, $\{u_{n}(t)\}$ has compact closure in $L^{2}$ for each $t>0$. But $u_{nt}=v_{n}$ and $v_{n}$ bounded in $L_{2}$ imply there is a constant $K_{5}$ such that

$$\begin{equation*} |u_{n}(t_{1})-u_{n}(t_{2})|_{L^{2}}\leq K_{5}|t_{1}-t_{2}| \end{equation*}$$

for all $t_{1}, t_{2}\geq 0$. This implies there is a subsequence of the $u_{n}(t)$ convergent in $L^{2}$ and so $\rho$ is a precompact pseudometric. Thus, $T(t_{1})$ is an $\alpha$-contraction by Lemma2.3.6.

The remainder of the proof of Theorem4.7.8 is completed as in the proof of Theorem4.7.1.

4.7.4. Periodic forcing.In this section, we consider equation (7.18) subjected to a periodic forcing function of period $p$ and show that the periodic map has a global compact attractor. In particular, this implies that there is a $p$-periodic solution of the forced equation.

Suppose $f$ satisfies (7.4), $h$ satisfies (7.17), and $e\!:R\rightarrow L^{2}$ is a continuous $p$-periodic function and consider the equation

7.26 $$\begin{equation} u_{t}=v,\quad \quad v_{t}=u_{xx}-h(v)+f(u)+e(t) \cssId{texmlid127}{\tag{7.26}} \end{equation}$$

with the Dirichlet conditions (7.2).
